%I A394418 #10 Apr 14 2026 08:43:23
%S A394418 1,2,4,6,3,9,12,10,14,8,16,18,15,20,22,24,21,27,30,28,32,26,34,17,51,
%T A394418 33,54,36,56,35,55,40,58,42,57,45,60,46,62,48,63,49,70,50,72,52,74,44,
%U A394418 76,38,78,39,81,66,82,68,84,69,87,75,85,80,86,88,90,92,94
%N A394418 a(1) = 1, a(2) = 2; for n > 2, a(n) is an unused positive number that shares a factor with a(n-1) while being as close as possible to a(n-2). If two such numbers exist then the larger is chosen.
%C A394418 The sequence uses a similar method to A394413 for choosing a(n) except here a(n) is chosen to be the larger of the two possible values when they are equal distances from a(n-2).
%C A394418 The terms are concentrated along two jagged lines that are initially close but separate after ~2500 terms, after which they generally remain separated but occasionally come together, with the lower line occasionally approaching the x-axis. See the attached images.
%C A394418 Overall the primes are rare, only 73 terms being prime in the first 10^8 terms, see A394419, and they do not occur in their natural order. In this range the smallest missing prime is 19, although, given the pattern of the lower line approaching the x-axis, it is conjectured eventually all numbers will appear.
%C A394418 There are sixteen fixed points in the first 10^8 terms, these being 1, 2, 9821, 9873, 9879, ..., 30816, 30818, 30820; it is likely more exist.
%H A394418 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A394418/b394418.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A394418 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A394418/a394418.png">Image of the first 100000 terms</a>. The colors are graduated across the spectrum from red to violet to show the total number of prime factors of each term, counted with multiplicity. The thin green line is a(n) = n.
%H A394418 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A394418/a394418_1.png">Image of the first 10000000 terms</a>. Despite the generally increasing trend in this image the lower line does eventually come back toward the x-axis, e.g., a(44096494) = 11.
%e A394418 a(8) = 10 as 10 is unused, shares a factor with a(7) = 12, and is only 1 away from a(6) = 9. This is the first term to differ from A394413. Note that 8 also satisfies these same criteria, but the larger of the two possible values is chosen.
%Y A394418 Cf. A394419 (prime terms), A394413, A064413, A386482, A394421.
